  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article titled \"COVID-19-associated neurological and psychological manifestations,\" published in Nature Reviews Disease Primers, explores significant neurological and psychological effects linked to COVID-19. Featuring contributions from prominent institutions such as Howard Hughes Medical Institute and the University of Milan, it has garnered attention, evidenced by nine citations across various disciplines.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This scholarly work investigates the complex interplay between COVID-19 and its resulting neurological and psychological manifestations, a topic of increasing relevance in the wake of the pandemic. The article has received nine citations since its publication, demonstrating its influence in the academic community and the growing interest in the long-term effects of COVID-19 on mental and neurological health.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Notably, this article has sparked discussion on the social media platform Bluesky, highlighting its resonance beyond academic circles. Such discourse signifies public engagement with the findings and may help raise awareness on the broader implications of COVID-19 on mental health, making the article relevant to both healthcare professionals and the general public.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Institutionally, the article benefits from the contributions of distinguished authors from leading organizations such as the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and the University of Milan. This collaboration reflects a commitment to high-quality research, indicating a well-supported investigation into this critical area of study.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, the work's impact is reinforced by its downstream reuse in diverse research contexts, evidenced by ten instances of proven reuse. This illustrates how the findings and insights have provided a basis for further inquiry into associated health issues, thus contributing to the evolution of knowledge in the field of neuropsychology related to COVID-19.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As the academic discourse surrounding the neurological and psychological consequences of COVID-19 continues to expand, this article stands as a significant resource for researchers and clinicians alike, shaping future studies and informing healthcare practices in the post-pandemic landscape.</p>",
